# Fluff Date: 2026-03-10 14:55:21
<overview>
<p>The Ranger Armored Fighting Vehicle is a wheeled combat vehicle produced by Valiant Systems of Johnsondale, entering service with the Armed Forces of the Federated Suns in 3076. Built on an expanded derivative of the company's Striker chassis, the Ranger trades some of that design's economy for heavier armament and substantially greater armor protection. The result is a vehicle purpose-built for close-range urban combat and infantry support, occupying a niche that the lighter Striker cannot fill. The Ranger's limited engagement range and persistent naming confusion with the Fox Armored Car have kept sales modest, but its low acquisition and maintenance costs have earned it a loyal following among mercenary commands and planetary defense forces that value affordability over battlefield versatility.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Ranger is built on a widened three-axle derivative of the Striker hull, the added axle necessary to handle the vehicle's 45-ton combat weight. The GM 250 fusion engine drives it to a flank speed of ninety-seven kilometers per hour, allowing it to keep pace with lancemates and reposition rapidly within urban terrain.</p><p>Ten tons of Valiant Buckler standard armor provides approximately thirty percent more protection than comparable vehicles in its class. That margin is significant given the design's close-range combat doctrine, which regularly places crews within direct engagement distance of their targets.</p><p>The primary armament centers on two Johnston SlavTrack arrays, each combining a Johnston Minigun with a Johnston Light Minigun. The linked configuration delivers mixed machine gun fire out to 120 meters, effective against both conventional and battle-armored infantry. Two Exostar ER Small Lasers supplement the arrays for modest ranged capability and serve as backup when ammunition runs low.</p><p>The Ranger carries notable limitations. Its sub-120-meter effective range forces crews to close under fire before the main armament becomes useful, placing heavy demands on the driver and commander. The SlavTrack arrays are maintenance-intensive, and the absence of anti-armor capability limits the vehicle to a specialist role rather than general-purpose employment.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>Introduced in 3082, the VV2 replaces the machine gun batteries entirely with eight Magshot Gauss rifles, nearly tripling the effective engagement range of the vehicle's primary armament. The trade-off is a significant reduction in volume of fire, making the VV2 less effective at close-range infantry suppression than the base model. The design has garnered more positive reviews among commanders who need a vehicle capable of engaging battle-armored infantry at distance, and the VV2 is frequently paired with one or two VV1s in urban defense lances. The VV1s manage close threats while the VV2 delivers ranged Gauss fire against harder targets, a combination that addresses the individual limitations of each model.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>Valiant Systems developed the Ranger as a direct extension of their Striker product line, drawing on existing chassis architecture and supplier relationships to reduce development time and cost. The design brief called for a vehicle capable of supporting AFFS infantry formations in dense urban terrain, where the Striker's armament was judged insufficient against armored infantry concentrations encountered during the later Jihad period. Adding a third axle and scaling to 45 tons gave the design team enough margin to fit the dual SlavTrack arrays and substantially heavier armor.</p><p>The Ranger entered service in 3076 and was immediately committed to post-Jihad stabilization operations. At Achernar, pairs of Rangers working alongside Morningstar Command Tanks proved effective against Protectorate Locusts and Word of Blake battle armor in the confined fighting around the BattleMech factory complex. The machine gun batteries demonstrated their value against power-armored infantry in close terrain, and the additional armor allowed crews to survive engagements that would have destroyed lighter vehicles.</p><p>Despite these early successes, broader AFFS adoption was limited by the vehicle's narrow utility. The restricted engagement range drew criticism from formation commanders accustomed to vehicles with greater battlefield flexibility, and most Rangers that survived their initial deployments were transferred from armor regiments to infantry support assignments. There they were paired with APCs and heavy infantry units, a role that suited the design far better.</p><p>Sales outside the AFFS remained modest, compounded by persistent market confusion with the Fox Armored Car's similar designation. Mercenary commands and corporations showed more consistent interest than House armies, drawn by the vehicle's low purchase price and straightforward logistics. The Republic of the Sphere became a reliable if small-volume customer, purchasing Rangers for planetary militia contracts through the Dark Age period. Valiant Systems continued refining the design through successive variants, incrementally addressing the range and maintenance criticisms that limited the base model's appeal.</p>
</history>

